1340","Bef 1368":"before 1368","1360":"1360","Abt 1362":"about 1362","Abt 1360":"about 1360","1368":"1368","about 1328":"about 1328","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1399":"1399","about 1358":"about 1358","1310":"1310","Abt 1330":"about 1330","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marschall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Hedwig, Juergen, Reinhard, Theresia, Wilfried.","German: occupational name for a man in the service of a member of the nobility, originally one who looked after the horses, Middle High German <i>marschalc</i> (from <i>mar(c)</i> ‘noble horse’ + <i>schalk</i> ‘servant’). In time the term came to be used for a military rank or a certain court official. Compare   Marshall  .","English: variant of   Marshall  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Marschel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Klaus.","German:","variant of   Marschall  ."]},{"name":"Marshall","meanings":["English: usually an occupational name ‘farrier’, occasionally a status name ‘chief official of a royal household or court; a high officer of state’, from Middle English <i>mareshal</i> and Old French <i>maresc(h)al</i>. An even wider range of meanings is found in some other languages: compare for example Polish <b>Marszałek</b> (see   Marszalek  ). This name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century. It is also borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Marschall  .","Americanized form of French   Mercier  ."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Heinrich","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>heim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’.  See  Henry ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Heinrich Marschall von Mockritz was born about 1330, his father, Heinrich Marschall von Mockritz, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. nn NN, was 22. He married Mrs. nn NN about 1358. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died after 1399."},"et":{"Abt 1330–Aft 1399":"umbes 1330–pärast 1399","1330–1399":"1330–1399","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1362–Male":"1362–Surnud","1300–1368":"1300–1368","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","Aft 1399":"pärast 1399","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","Bef 1368":"enne 1368","1360":"1360","Abt 1362":"umbes 1362","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1368":"1368","about 1328":"umbes 1328","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1399":"1399","about 1358":"umbes 1358","1310":"1310","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330"},"fi":{"Abt 1330–Aft 1399":"noin 1330–1399 jälkeen","1330–1399":"1330–1399","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1360–1410":"1360–1410","1362–Male":"1362–Kuollut","1300–1368":"1300–1368","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","Aft 1399":"1399 jälkeen","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","Bef 1368":"ennen vuotta 1368","1360":"1360","Abt 1